{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_havarti_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542869008/1927062301/0452.xml":{"full_text":"BANK TRANSACTIONS\nWednesday, June 22, 1927\n$21,678,183\nAll banks reported.\nIron and Steel Market Lapses Into Dullness of Summer\nOUTPUT IS CUT\n78 PER CENT;\nBY U. S. \u2018SUBS\u2019\nSpotty Price Outlook\nSequel to\nLull.\nThe iron and steel market is laps\ning into a summer lull, according\nto the weekly reviews of the trade.\nThe industry is drifting into the\nthird quarter with the interest of\nconsumers lagging beyond expecta\ntions, Iron Trade Review asserts,\nanl Iron Age says that steel busi\nness is at a slow pace, to continue\nuntil August.\nOutput Is Slashed.\n\u201cProduction has been further cur\ntailed, United States Steel corpora\ntion subsidiaries reducing their\nsteel making rate to 78 per cent,\nwhile independent operations have\nshrunk to about 70 per cent,\u201d Iron\nTrade Review reports.\n\u201cTwo steel works stacks were\nblown out at Chicago, making four\ndropped in three weeks. At no time\nin the first half year have produc\ners retrenched so sharply as in the\nlast fortnight.\u201d\nLast year at this time the out\nlook began to brighten and prices\nbegan to strengthen, although de\nmand did not require expansion in\nproduction for some weeks, Iron\nAge points out, announcing that re\nduction in output this week has\nbroeght the industry some 10 per\ncent under the operating position it\nheld a year ago.\nPrice Is Spotty.\nA spotty price situation is the\nsequel to the scanty buying of con\nsumers, it is stated. Pig iron prices\nare off?s cents a ton in the eastern\nPennsylvania district, and quota\ntions in almost all other districts\nare said to be easy.\nChicago mills, Iron Trade said,\nare entertaining inquiry for 120,000\ntons of rails, including 50,000 tons\nfor the Pennsylvania, and an ac\ncompanying 35,000 tons of track\nfastenings.\nBoth of the Iron Age composite\nprices are uncertain from last week,\npig iron at .$18.96 a gross ton, and\nfinished steel at 2.3G7 cents a\npound.\n\u201cDemand for iron and steel scrap\nalong the Atlantic seaboard for ex\nport to Europe reached fair propor\ntions in the last week and aroused\ndealers\u2019 hope that the tide of re\nceding prices may be turned,\u201d said\nIron Trade Review.\nMilwaukee Livestock\nHOGS\u2014 Receipts, 1,800; steady to 10c\nlower.\nPrime heavy and butchers,\n200 lbs. up .....I 8.25@ 8.80\nPrime heavy and butchers.\n91A-2KO lbs B.oo<g/ y.iu\nFair to good lights, 160-200 8.50@ 025\nFresh light lights, 130-160.. 7.75@ 8.7.>\nFair to select packers 7.60@ 8.00\nRough and greasy 6.00@ 7.2.\nHairless and rough skinned\nITb\nGovernment throwouts I.o\u00b0@ 6.00\nCATTLE \u2014Receipts, 400; 10@15c lower.\nSteers, good to choice\nMedium to good o'nn^q'oo\nFair to medium HnS 7 nn\nHeifers, good to choice 7.00\u00ae 950\nMedium to good 6.00\u00ae I'H\nFair to medium Hn\nCommon to fair 6.00\u00ae 6.00\nCows, good to choice 6.75\u00ae 6.26\nMedium to good\nFair to medium 0.25@ 5.i5\nCutter 5.15\nCanners 4.25\u00ae t 'Sr\nButchers\u2019 bulls 6.50\u00ae 6.75\nBologna hulls 6.75\u00ae 6.25\nMilkers and springers, good\nto choice (common sell\nfor beef) 60.00@120.00\nCALVES\u2014Receipts, 2,000; 50c lower.\nGood to choice, 100 lbs. up.511.00@11.50\nFair to good 10.50@11.00\nThrowouts 6.00\nSHEEP\u2014Receipts. 300; steady.\nGood to choice aprlng lambssl3.oo@l4.so\nFair to good spring iambs.. 11.50@12.50\nCull lambs ........J....... 7.00\u00a910.00\nLight ewes 6.00@ 6.00\nHeavy ewes 3.50\u00ae 4.50\nCull ewes I.oo\u00ae 3.00\nBucks 3.00\u00ae 3.50\nMilwaukee Produce Prices\u2014Corrected Daily\nDAIRY MARKETS.\nButter\u2014 Creamery, fresh, extras, tubs.\n?9V*c: extra firsts. 3S@39c; firsts, 35\u00ae\n37c; seconds, 32@34c; centralized, BSto\nS 9 score. 39c: ladles, 32\u00ae34c; packing\nstock No. I, 33\u00ae27c; off-stock, 15\u00ae30c.\nCheese American, full cream, twins,\n22 \u00ae22 \u2018jc; daisies, single. 22%@23c;\ndouble. 22**\u00ae23c; Young Americas, 23\u00ae\n23%c; longhorns, 23\u00ae23%c; squares,\n23% \u00ae24c. 6-lb. loaves \u2014American, 31\u00ae\nS3c; pimento, S4@36c; brick, 32\u00ae34c;\nSwiss, 38\u00ae41c. Special makes \u2014Brick,\nfancy, 22@22%c; limburger, winter\nmake. 21\u00ae21%c; Swiss, block, 26@29c;\nloaf. 30\u00ae36c; imported. Swiss. 42\u00ae45c.\nEggs\u2014Fresh-gathered firsts, standard\ncases included, 22%@22\u00ab\u00a3c; ordinary\nfirsts, shippers\u2019 cases included, 19\u00ae20c;\nstorage packed, 23\u00ae24c; dirties, candled,\n17%@18c; seconds, checks, candled, 16\u2019*:\n17c.\nMEATS AND POULTRY.\nPigeons Old flyers, live, per doz.,\n$1.50 <Q> 1.75; dead, $1.00@1.25; squabs,\nlive, per doz.. $2.00@2.50; dressed, fat.\n$3 00@3.50; thin, poorly dressed, $1..10@\n1.50.\nPoultry Live Fowls. 4 'os.\nand over, 20c; under 4 lbs., 17c: r -t\ners, old or staggy young. 14c:\n,-rs, over 2 lbs., 33c; broilers, 1% t*\n2 lbs., 27c; legnom springeis.\nlbs., 26c; leghorn broilers. 1 lbs. and\nup, 24c: turkeys, plump, 25c: ducks, old\nor young, 23c; geese, old. 14c; Guinea\nhens, per aoz., young. $5.00. t\nYea!\u2014Calves. 50 to 60 lbs.. fair kid\nneys, 13c; 60 to 70 lbs., choice, meaty.\n14c: 70 to 80 lbs., good kidneys, 15c;\n80 to 90 lbs., choice, 16c; 90 to 110 lbs.,\nfancy. 17c: extra fancy, 18c; thin. bmy.\nf*oor kidneys, poorly dressed or off-stock,\n80 to 175 lbs., as to quality and condi\ntion. 9@llc.\nHides\u2014Calf, green, 17c; cured, 18c;\nkips, green 12c; cured, 13c; cow green,\n7c; cured. 8c; bull, green, 6c; cured, 6c;\ndeacons, green, each, 60c; slunk, green,\neach 25c; horse No. 1, green, each $3.50;\ndo, No. 2 green, each. $2.26; pelts, green,\neach, 60c@51.60.\nFRUITS.\nApples\u2014Eastern, barrels. $5.25\u00ae 7.00;\nWestern, boxes, Delicious, $4.50\u00ae 5.00:\nWine Saps. $3.60@3.75.\nNew Apples\u2014Southern, per bu. t $3.00\n0 4.00.\nApricots\u2014Calif., 4-basket crates, $2.50\n@2.76.\nBananas\u2014fer 100 lbs., 55.60@6.50.\nCherries\u2014California. 8-lb. boxes $3.00\n@3.60; lugs, 26 lbs?.* Royal Anns, $3.00\u00ae\nI with Vfie\nb-ptWEDM,\nThe highest price paid for milk\nin May, since that month of 1920,\nwas paid during the past month of\nthis year\u2014sl.9B per hundredweight,\nbeing the average Wisconsin farm\nmilk price, according to figures\ncompiled by the Wisconsin live\nstock and crop service.\nThe May price of this year was\n18 cents above the May, 1920, price,\nand 15 cents above May, 1925. It\nwas 34 cents per hundredweight\nabove the May average price of the\nlast six years.\nPrices on dairy products have\nbeen relatively stable also, the bu\nreau reports, cheese prices holding\nup particularly well.\nFeed prices are reported lower\nthan they were during the previous\ntwo years, but the outlook for the\nhay crop in Wisconsin is very good.\nHeavy Gold Imports.\nA jump of $31,277,000 over May,\n192(5, was set by the $34,212,000 im\nports of gold recorded during the\npast month, it is revealed in figures\nreleased today. For the first five\nmonths of the year gold imports\ntotaled $146,761,000, as against\n$104,231,000 last year. The large\nincrease in May was attributed to\nheavy shipment of 18,000,000 pounds\ngold by the Rank of France from\nthe Bank of England.\nMerchandise foreign trade during\nMay showed an increase over last\nyear with imports of $346,000,000\nand exports of $394,000,000, compar\ning with $321,029,000 and $356,621,-\n000 respectively for May last year.\nResults of May foreign trade indi\ncate export surplus for the United\nStates of more than $700,000,000 for\nthe fiscal year ended June 30.\nBanks Buy Bonds.\nMore* than $110,387,000 worth of\ndomestic securities and foreign gov\nernment bonds were owned in 1926\nby Wisconsin national banks and of\nthis amount, $245,000 was invested\nin Russian, German and Austrian\ngovernment bonds and $3,760,000 in\nbonds of other foreign governments,\nsays the controller of currency.\nUnited States government securi\nties were popular with Wisconsin,\n$1,328,000 having been invested in\nthese securities by the national\nbanks of the Badger state of 1926.\nIn state, county, and municipal\nbonds, Wisconsin bankers had $13,-\n219,000 invested at the close of the\nyear.\nIn federal reserve bank stock, the\nnational banks of Wisconsin had in\nvested the sum of $1,241,000 at the\nclose of 1926.\nASK QUICK ERIE\nMERGER RULING\nWASHINGTON The interstate\ncommerce commission\u2019s hearings on\nthe Chesapeake Ohio $1,000,000,-\n000 railroad merger were brought to\na close here yesterday with a last\nminute appeal by the proponents of\nthe unification for a speedy deter\nmination of the case.\nO. P. and M. J. Van Sweringen,\nCleveland, chief backers of the\nmerger, seek to join the Erie and\nPere Marquette with the Chesa\npeake Ohio into a huge steam\ntransportation system.\nIn their final plea to the com\nmission yesterday Van Sweringen\u2019s\nlawyers declared that if the com\nmission will decide the ease before\nJuly 1 the Chesapeake Ohio eah\ntake advantage of an option it has\nfrom the Nickel Plate for a block\nof Pere Marquette stock, which was\nagreed to be sold at a price under\nthe present market quotations.\nIf the commission defers its de\ncision until after July 1 the shares\ncannot be obtained except at much\nhigher prices, they declared.\n4,00; Tarfarlans, $4.00@4.50; Bings, $6.00\n@7.00.\nLemons California, per box, $7.00\u00ae\n7.50.\nLimes\u2014lmported, 101), $2.50 @3.00.\nOranges California, Valencias, per\nbox, as to size and quality, $5.50@7.50;\nFlorida, Indiana Rivers, $6,00@7.00.\nPeaches Georgia, 6-basket crates,\n$3.00@3.25; bushels. $3.25@3.50.\nPears\u2014Western, poxes,-Win ter Welles,\n$5.50 6.00.\nPineapples\u2014Cuban, crate, $3.50@4.50.\nPlums\u2014Calif., 4-basket crates, $2.25\u00ae\n2.75.\nMELONS.\nCantaloupes\u2014Calif., standard crates,\n$4.25@4.50; pony crates, $3.75@4.00;\ni Jumbos, $4.50@4.75; flats, $1.25@1.50.\nWatermellons Florida, apiece, 40\u00ae\n50c; Texas, 60 @7 sc.\nBERRIES.\nStrawberries\u2014Michigan or Wisconsin.\n16 qt. cases, $2.50@3.00; home-grown,\n$4.00@4.50.\nRaspberries\u2014Washington. 12 pt. cases,\n$2.75@3.00.\nVEGETABLES.\nAsparagus Illinois, sections, 24\nbunches. $2.00@2.25; Ashton. $2.25@2.50;\nhome-grown, doz. punches, $1.00@1.25.\nBeets \u2014St. Louis, bushels. $1.25@1.00;\ni Mississippi, hampers, $1.00@1.25; home-\nI grown, doz. bunches. 65@75e.\nCabbage\u2014Tennessee, pony crates, $2.25\n@2.50; bulk, Missouri, per bbl., $5.00\u00ae\n5.50.\nCarrots\u2014California, crate. $3.50@3.75.\nCauliflower\u2014California, crate, $3.50\u00ae\n3.75.\nCelery\u2014California, crate. SIO.OO 14.00;\nFlorida, $6.00 @7.00, Michigan, boxes,\n$3.25@3.50.\nCelery Root \u2014Home-grown, doz., as to\nsize, 25\u00ae60c.\nCucumbers\u2014Hot house, boxes, 2 doz..\n$2.50@3.25; Florida, hampers, $3.50\u00ae\n3.75.\nEgg Plant\u2014Florida, crate, $5.00@5.60.\nGarlic\u2014California, per lb., 6\u00aeBc.\nGreen Peas\u2014lndiana, bushel. $4.00\u00ae\n4.25; Eastern, hampers, $3.75@4.00.\nHorseradish Southern, root, per lb.,\nfancy, thick. B@loc.\nLeek Home-grown, per bunch. 12\nstalks, large. 40c; small. 25@30c.\nLettuce Leaf\u2014Home-grown, bushels,\nout-door. 60\u00ae75c.\nLettuce\u2014tread\u2014Teeberg, fancy, West\nern. f.00@4.50 off-stock. $2.00 @3.00;\nhome-grown, box or busgei, i\nThe Leader Financial Page\nTWELVE\nTHORNTON SEES\nGOOD YEAR FOR\nCANADIAN LINES\nMONTREAL\u2014\u201cI think 1927 is\ngoing to prove a very good year for\nus,\u201d Sir Henry Thornton, president\nof the Canadian National Railways,\nsaid today in reviewing business\nconditions as reflected by the traf\nfic on Canada's great national\ntransportation system.\n\u201cAll the signs point to a most\nprofitable business year. I believe\nthat the Dominion of Canada is\nnow enjoying a period of expansion\nand natural progress that will con\ntinue to bring to the country\u2019s\ntransportation systems a steadily\ncontinuing increase in business and\nI am convinced that this era of ex\npansion will result in good times\nthroughout the whole of the Domin\nion for a period of years.\nReports from officials of the\nfreight department of the Canadian\nNational indicate that this branch\nof the business throughout the sys\ntem is likely to improve upon the\nsatisfactory showing made during\nthe past few years, while passen\nger traffic is also reported to be\non the increase, although 1926 was\nregarded as a record year in this\nrespect.\nAlthough the operating income of\nthe Canadian National increased\nfrom $3,000,000 in 1922 to over $48,-\n000.000 in 1926, the end of this re\nmarkable financial improvement has\nnot by any means been reached, ac\ncording to President Thornton.\n\u201cI have every confidence that the\nbest years of the Canadian Nation\nal are in the future,\u201d he told re\nporters here today.\nMay Brings Jump\nIn Ordinary Life\nInsurance Sales\nNEW YORK\u2014The sales of ordi\nnary life insurance in the United\nStates and Canada during May\nshowed a decided increase, accord\ning to figures just issued by the\nLife Insurance Sales Research bur\neau of Hartford, Conn. The vol\nume for the United States totals\n$752,267,000, which is larger than\nany previous May on record.\nThis report includes the produc\ntion of new paid-for ordinary in\nsurance exclusive of revivals, in\ncreases, dividend additions, rein\nsurance from other companies and\ngroup insurance us reported by 81\ncompanies having in force 88 per\ncent of the total life insurance out\nstanding in the United States legal\nreserve companies.\nIn Canada 18 per cent more ordi\nnary life insurances was purchased\nduring May than in May, 1926. New\nbusiness paid for by companies hav\ning in force 84 per cent of the to\ntal outstanding business in Canada\namounted to $44,553,000.\nCUTS DISCOUNT RATE.\nBOMBAY, India\u2014The Imperial\nBank of India today reduced its dis\ncount rate from six per cent to\nfive.\nRailroads Seek\nRate Czar; Plan\nBelieved Feasible\nNEW YORK\u2014The North West\nern road\u2019s plan to select a \u201crate\nczar\u201d to have full control of all\ntariff schedules presented to the\ninterstate commerce commission\nwould, it Is believed, enable the\nrailways to overcome the obstacle\nof unbridled competition and would\ndo much toward the earning of a\n\u201cfair return,\u201d in the opinion of F.\nJ. Lisman, banker.\nThe only difficulty, he thinks,\nwould he in finding a man of suf\nficient standing for such a position.\nThe appointment of a \u201cdictator\u201d\nwith sufficient secretarial assist\nance to carry out the plan would\nsolve many of the rate problems of\nthe northwest, the hanker believes.\nMusnrooms\u2014Per lb., No. 1, 1-lb. boxes,\n70@75c: buttons. 60@65c.\nOnions Texas, sacks, per 100 lbs.,\n$5.75@6.00; new. Texas, crate, yellow,\n$3.25@3.50; white, $3.50\u00ae3.75.\nOyster Plant\u2014Per doz. bunches, SI.OO\n@l.lO.\nParsley Home-grown, dozen small\nlunches. 25\u00ae30c.\nParsnips Home-grown, bu.. washed,\n$1.15@1.25; unwashed. 65@75c.\nPeppers Louisiana, hampers, $1.75\u00ae\n2.25.\nPieplant\u2014Home-grown, doz. bunches.\n20 25c.\nPotatoes Minnesota, Michigan, Wis\nconsin, sacks. 100 lbs., white stock, on\ntrack, $2.50@2.75.\nPotatoes New\u2014Carolina, bbls., cob\nblers No. 1, $6.50@7.00; sacked, per 100\nlbs.. $4.25@4.50.\nRadlsnes rrome-grown, doz. bchs.,\noutdoor. 12%@15c.\nRutabagas Canadian, per 106 lbs.,\n$3.50@4.00.\nSpinach Home-grown, bushel, 65\u00ae\n75c.\nString Beans Louisiana, hampers,\nwax or green. $3.00@3.50; Tennessee,\nclimax baskets. $1.00@1.25.\nTomatoes Blorida, repacked, 6-bas\nket crates. $5.00 @3.50; Mississippi, 4-\nbasket crates. $1.00@1.25; home-gr >wn,\nhot house, lb.. 15@lSc.\nTurnips\u2014New, Texas, bushel. $2.00\u00ae\n2.50.\nPRODCCE MARKETS.\nBeans Navies, choice, hand picked,\nper 100 lbs. (sacks Included), $5.00\u00ae\n5.25; Red Kidney, $7.00@7 50; Brown\nSwedish, $6.00@6.50; Lima Beans, Cali\nfornia. J7.50@8.00.\nBees Wax Choice to fancy, per lb.,\nbright. 28@30c; dark, 23@25c, and\ndown to 20e.\nHoney Comb, per cases, 25 X-lb. sec\ntions, fancy, white, $4.75@5.00; dark,\n$4.25@4.50; mixed sells at around $4.25.\nExtracted, lb., white clover, ll@12c;\namber, 9@loc.\nTeas\u2014Per 100 lbs. i new 100-lb. sacks),\ngreen. $3.25; Scotch, $3.50; white. $4.50;\nmarrow fats. $5.50: split Peas, yellow,\n$5.75@fi.00; green, $5 75 @6.00.\nPop Corn\u2014Qnotanic per 100 lbs. ears,\n$3.00@3.50; shelled. do. $4.00@5.00;\nbroken, poor. less.\nTallow\u2014Prime. 9%@10c; No. 1, solid,\n6%@7c; No. 2,6% @6c: cakes, 7t*>@Bc:\nrough, 2%@Sc.\nWool\u2014Medium, per lb., 30@S2e: low.\nJ 8\nuaes MgiSa\u00dffcY -s ...i.\nMILWAUKEE, THURSDAY, JUNE 23, 1927\nCALLS FOREIGN\nLOANS NEEDED\nFOR PROSPERITY\nMADlSON\u2014Foreign loans are\nnecessary for the continuation of\nAmerican prosperity, Melvin E.\nTraylor, president of the American\nBankers\u2019 Assn., told 800 bankers at\ntending the annual convention of the\nWisconsin Bankers\u2019 Assn, here yes\nterday.\nMr. Traylor declared that Ameri\ncan bankers are the custodians of\nthe world\u2019s credit as a result of the\nwar and that the bankers must\ndivide credit so that the nation may\nprosper and the world with it.\n\u201cIf we quit making foreign loans\nwe will lose our financial aid. In\ndustrial supremacy and our prosper\nity will go with it,\u201d Mr. Traylor\ndeclared.\nMr. Traylor pointed to the na\ntion\u2019s hank failures and declared\nthat the failing institutions were as\na whole the small ones. He recom\nmended two remedies for banking\ntroubles. One would be legislation\nby the state to prohibit the charter\ning of hanks with a capitalization of\nless than $25,000 and the other pro\nhibiting the payment of dividends\nover the rate on savings until the\nsurplus equals the capital.\nRAIL WORKING\nSTABILITY ASKED\nWASHINGTON \u2014The desirability\nof bringing about as great stability\nof employment on the railroads of\nthis country as earnings, traffic and\nclimatic conditions permit, is rec\nognized in a report just submitted\nto member roads of the association\nof the railway executives by a spe\ncial committee appointed in 1924.\nThe members of the special com\nmittee were Daniel Willard, presi\ndent of the Baltimore Ohio, chair\nman; L. W. Baldwin, president of\nthe Missouri Pacific; H. E. Byram,\nreceiver of the Milwaukee road; W.\nH. Cole, president of the Louisville\nNashville; P. E. Crowley, presi\ndent of the New York Central lines\nC. li. Gray, president of the Union\nPacific system; L. F. Loree, presi\ndent of the Delaware Hudson;\nE. J. Pearson, president of the New\nYork, New Haven Hartford, and\nSamuel Rea, former president of the\nPennsylvania.\n\u201cYour committee,\u201d said the report,\nis convinced that stability of em\nployment is invariably reflected in\nmore efficient and economical op\nerations.\n\u201cWhile there seems to be a gen\neral tendency at the present time to\nrecognize the eight-hour day in most\nlines of employment there is much\nto be said in favor of a certain\nelasticity in the number of hours\nto he worked. If the day could be\nincreased from 8 to 9 and even 10\nhours in times of business activity\nsuch a policy would enable the car\nriers to employ a more uniform force\nthroughout the year and avoid the\nnecessity of laying off or furlough\ning large numbers of men in times\nof business recession.\u201d\nTreasury Surplus\nNear $603,000,000\nWASHINGTON The treasury\nsurplus, watched closely by both po\nlitical parties for the light it will\nthrow upon how far congress can\ngo in cutting taxes next winter,\nwill be* about $603,000,000, latest\nofficial figures indicated today.\nJune income tax collections are\nrunning $22,000,000 ahead of last\nyear, with $224,000,000 recorded on\nthe treasury books up to last Fri\nday night.\nN.Y. Stock Market Closing Prices\nWednesday\nClose.\nAmerican Sugar Refining 90\nAmerican Tel, and Tel 163%\nAmerican Tobacco B 133%\nAmerican Woolen 20\nAmer. Zinc, Lead and Smelt. 7%\nAnaconda Copper 43%\nA. T. and S. F 180%\nA. T. and S. F. pfd 102%\nBaldwin Locomotive 225%\nBaltimore and Ohio 117%\nBethlehem Steel 49%\nCalifornia Packing 62\nCalifornia Petroleum 22%\nCanadian Pacific 180\nCase (J. I.) Threshing 219\nCentral Leather 15%\nCerro de Pasco 19%\nChesapeake and Ohio 180%\nChicago Great Western 17%\nC. M. and St. P 17\nC. M. and St. P. pfd 32%\nC. and N. W 87%\nC. R. I. and P 112%\nChile Copper 34%\nChrysler Motors 47%\nColorado Fuel and Iron 86\nConsolidated Gas 101%\nCorn Products Ref 54\nDupont 242%\nElectric P. and L. ctfs 21%\nErie Railroad 52%\nGeneral Asphalt 75%\nGeneral Cigar Co 66%\nGeneral Electric 105\nGeneral Motors 200%\nGoodrich B F 54\nGreat Northern pfd 91%\nGreat Northern ctfs 18%\nGreene Cananea 44%\nHudson Motors 82%\nIllinois Central 120%\nIndian Ref 8%\nInspiration Copper 14\nInternational Harvester 183%\nInternational Mereli. Marine 7%\nInternational Paper 42%\nKansas City Southern 60%\nKennecott Copper 62%\nKresge S. S 55%\nLehigh Valley 127\nMarlancl Ull 34%\n9^HOMEJi*N\nmwmmmn\nEndive and Esearolle for Fall\nCUfttY\nENDIVE.\n\u2014\u00ab=s-H\"S\u00a3^<w^..JaSia^/\u00b1^^\nSW^D LEAVED OR ESCAROLLE.\nCurly endive, which makes such\nan attractive display in the falL\nwith its finely cut and snow-white\nhearts as well as the broad leaved\nor esearolle, should be started now.\nSow the seed in a well prepared\nseed bed precisely as the early\nspring lettuce was sown.\nAs soon as the seedlings have\nmade two or three true leaves move\nthem to their permanent rows. It\nis even better practice to transplant\ntwice, setting them two or three\ninches high in a shaded bed or cold\nframe and waiting until the middle\nof August to put them in permanent\nquarters.\nThe final transplanting should\nfind them a foot apart in the row.\nThey need good cultivation and in\ndroughts should be given an occa\nsional soaking. This consists of\ngathering up the tips of the outer\nleaves and tying them so that the\nheart is protected from the sun.\nAnother system is to set a flower\npot over the heart of the plant, sup\nporting it so that it*does not bear\ndown upon the leaves.\nAfter rains the leaves must be un\ntied long enough to allow the heart\nto dry out or it may rot or show\nbrown spots. The blanching process\nshould be carried along on the in\nstallment plan in order not to bring\nPRIMARY GRAIN MOVEMENT.\nPrimary car receipts today follow:\nWht. Corn Oats Barley Rye\nMilwaukee. 25 48 24 7 2\nChicago 20 149 38 4\nMinneapolis 133 31 7 43 j\nDuluth 113 32 14\nWinnipeg 83 7 8 1\nKansas City 31 26 4\nSt. Louis 39 60 12\nOmaha 11 32 40\nSt. Joseph .3 15 1\nMILWAUKEE FLOUR AND SEEDS.\nClover Seed\u2014Red, per 100 lbs., choice\nto fancy, $32.00 @36.00; country mts,\n$25.00@30.00; dirty, $21.00@25.00; alsike,\n$27.00@34.00; white. $20.00@30.00, Mixed\nlower.\nTimothy Seed Quotable $4.50 @5.00,\naccording to quality for country lots;\nfancy, $5.25.\nFlaxseed Basis Minneapolis freight\nNo. 1 N. W\u201e $2.15@2.2G; bag lots dis\ncounted s@lsc.\nFlour Straight, $7.50@7.65; patent,\n$7.65@7.90; clear, $6.40@6.90. Rye-\nStraight, $6.30 @6.55; patent. $6.45@6.65;\ndark, $5.65@85.\nMillstuffs \u2014Sacked bran, $28.00@28.50;\nstandard middlings, $31.00@31.50; flour\nmiddlings. $36.00@37.00; oil meal, $48.00\n@49.00, 100-lb. sacks. Gluten feed, $35.40.\nBeans Navy\u2014Bag lots, $4.50@5.00\nper 100-lb. sacks.\nPopcorn\u2014Per 100 lbs., $2.50@3.00.\nBuckwheat\u2014Silver hull, per 100 lbs.,\n$2.20@2.35; Japanese, $2.30@2.40, sub\nject to dockage.\nSpeltz\u2014Per 100 lbs., $1.13@1.25.\nWednesday\nClose.\nMiami Copper 14\nMissouri, Kansas and Texas 52%\nMissouri Pacific 57%\nMontgomery Ward 66%\nNational Biscuit 123%\nNational Lead 101\nNevada Cons. Copper 13%\nNew York Central 152\nN. Y. N. H. and Hart 53%\nNorthern Pacific SB%\nPacific Gas and Electric 36%\nPacific Oil 1%\nPan Amu. Petroleum 57%\nPennsylvania R. R 62%\nPure Oil 26%,\nRay Cons. Copper 14%\nReading 117%\nRepublic Iron 65%\nReynolds Tobacco \u201cB\u201d 136%\nRoyal Dutch 49\nSears, Roebuck 55%\nShell Union 27\nSinclair Cons. Oil 16%\nSouthern Pacific 113%\nSouthern R. R 126%\nStandard Oil Calif 53%\nStandard Oil of New Jersey.... 36%\nStudebaker* 49%\nTennessee Copper and Chem.... 8%\nTexco 47%\nTexas and Pacific 101\nTimken Bearing 100%\nTobacco Products 102%\nTranscontinental Oil 8%\nUnion Oil of California 42\nUnion Pacific 172%\nUnited States Rubber 40%\nUnited States Steel 120%\nUnited States Steel pfd 132%\nVanadium 47\nVirgin. Caro. Chemical 8\nWabash 76\nWahasli pfd A 100%\nWestern Union 162\nWostinghouse 74%\nWillvs-Overlnnd 19\nYellow T. and C 31%\nTOLEDO SEED MARKET.\nTOLEDO Clover, imported, cash,\n$13.75; October, $10.95; domestic, De\ncember. SIO.BO Alsike. August. $14.35:\nTimothy, cash. old. $2.45; cash, :ic\"\n?2.55i JJeteajifcer,\nthe whole crop to a state of white\nness at once, but blanching only\nenough for day to day use.\nThe broad leaved endive or esca\nrolle often is not blanched hut is\nbetter for a slight blanching as it\nmay be tough if not so treated. A\nwhite curled variety is sold which\nadapts itself to blanching more\nquickly than the green curled but\nthere is little if any difference, in\ntheir quality.\nCurly endive is a useful fall salad\nplant, coming into season when let\ntuce is out of the garden and pretty\nwell off the market and then very\nexpensive. It is very easy to raise.\nOne well developed plant is suf\nficient for one serving for the aver\nage family, so a couple of dozen\nplants is an ample supply for the\nfall salad season. The curly makes\na much larger growth than the\nbroad leaved or esearolle type.\nCASH WHEAT\nTRADE IN N. Y.\nNEW YORK\u2014Trading in cash\nwheat was begun yesterday on the\nNew Y T ork Produce Exchange and\nnearly 1,000,000 bushels were dealt\nin during the day. The new move\nmarks the evolution of the produce\nexchange into a complete grain ex\nchange.\nTrading in cash options on oats,\nrye and flax would start soon, he\nsaid.\nDenial that the establishment of\na cash market in New York was an\nattempt to capitalize the misfortunes\nof the Chicago Board of Trade and\nsteal its business was made by Axel\nI-lansen, who was the chief organ\nizer of the grain market here.\nDeliveries for the cash option in\nNew York trading are to he made\nat Buffalo, ,or on the basis of the\ncost there. Buffalo has an elevator\ncapacity of over 25.000.000 bushels,\nnearly two-thirds of the evelvator\ncapacity at Chicago. In addition,\nto export grain sent from the west,\nBuffalo also receives considerable\ngrain direct from the farms and lo\ncal elevators in Ohio and Indiana.\nChicago Produce\nCHICAGO Butter \u2014Receipts, 10.514;\ncreameries. 38*4 @39c; standards, 39%c;\nfirsts, 36@37c: seconds, 33@35%c; ex\ntras, 39%c. Eggs\u2014Receipts, 11,591: or\ndinaries, 20\u00ae 21c: extra firsts, 23 %c;\nfirsts, 22@23c; seconds, 19%c; extras,\n23%e. Cheese\u2014Twins, 22%@22%c;\nYoung Americas, 23 %c. Poultry\u2014Re\nceipts, four cars; fowls, 20c; springers,\n35c; roosters, 13c; ducks, 22c; geese, 13c;\nspring geese, 20c; turkeys, 20c; broilers.\n27c; leghorn springers, 25c; leghorn\nbroilers, 21 23c. Potatoes \u2014Arrivals,\n126 cars; on track, 2(j7; in transit, 815;\nOklahoma and Arkansas sacked Irish\ncobblers, few sales; ordinary, $3.50.\nSweet potatoes\u2014sl.oo @1.20.\nNew York Produce\nNEW YORK\u2014Flour, dull and un\nchanged. Pork, steady; mess, $33.00.\nLard, dull; midwest spot, $13.05@ 13.15.\nSugar, raw, steady: spot, 96 test, deliv\nered duty paid, $4.59; refined steady;\ngranulated, $6.10 @6.20. Coffee. Rio No.\n7 on spot. 14%c; Santos No. 4, 16% \u00a9l7c.\nTallow, steady; special to extra. 7%@\n7%c. Hay, easier No. 1, $1.20591.25;\nNo. 3, SI.OO @1.05; clover, 95c@51.15..\nDressed poultry, quiet; turkeys. 25@46c;\nchickens, 20@38c; broilers, 2S@42c; ca\npons, 30 46c; fowls, 14\u00ae28c; ducks. 18\n@22c; ducks, Long Islands, 23@24c. Live\npoultry, quiet; geese, 10@12c; duck